1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,420
"The stock market is doomed,
and I'm selling everything."

2
00:00:03,420 --> 00:00:05,220
This is the type of comment I'm seeing

3
00:00:05,220 --> 00:00:07,140
all over social media right now.

4
00:00:07,140 --> 00:00:10,230
I get it, everything's
taken a sudden dive,

5
00:00:10,230 --> 00:00:11,760
from stocks to crypto.

6
00:00:11,760 --> 00:00:13,740
And I know a lot of you
who watch my channel

7
00:00:13,740 --> 00:00:15,330
have just started investing.

8
00:00:15,330 --> 00:00:18,810
So for you guys, this is
understandably pretty worrying.

9
00:00:18,810 --> 00:00:20,460
So today, I thought it was important

10
00:00:20,460 --> 00:00:21,870
to address your concerns,

11
00:00:21,870 --> 00:00:24,330
explain what's causing all this mayhem,

12
00:00:24,330 --> 00:00:26,280
and finally, give you my thoughts

13
00:00:26,280 --> 00:00:28,320
on how you can best navigate this storm.

14
00:00:28,320 --> 00:00:30,510
I'm prioritizing getting
this video out quickly,

15
00:00:30,510 --> 00:00:33,990
so don't expect the editing
to be as slick as usual.

16
00:00:33,990 --> 00:00:36,840
It's more important for
you to hear the information

17
00:00:36,840 --> 00:00:39,090
so you can use it to your advantage.

18
00:00:39,090 --> 00:00:41,970
This is one video you
should definitely not skip.

19
00:00:41,970 --> 00:00:44,700
So why is the stock market plummeting?

20
00:00:44,700 --> 00:00:48,930
To put this into perspective,
the S&P 500 dropped 3%,

21
00:00:48,930 --> 00:00:52,320
which was the biggest one-day
drop in nearly two years.

22
00:00:52,320 --> 00:00:54,638
The Dow dropped 2.6%,

23
00:00:54,638 --> 00:00:57,600
while the NASDAQ slipped 3.4%.

24
00:00:57,600 --> 00:00:59,400
This sounds pretty alarming.

25
00:00:59,400 --> 00:01:02,340
And from my research, there
are four main reasons for this.

26
00:01:02,340 --> 00:01:05,610
So let's go through them one
by one so that we can see

27
00:01:05,610 --> 00:01:07,950
if we're due another historic market crash

28
00:01:07,950 --> 00:01:11,130
similar to the 2008 financial crisis

29
00:01:11,130 --> 00:01:13,080
or just a little bump along the road.

30
00:01:13,080 --> 00:01:16,080
Reason one, of course,
is the fear of recession.

31
00:01:16,080 --> 00:01:18,390
Now, if the economy went into a recession,

32
00:01:18,390 --> 00:01:21,060
the stock market would
most likely plummet.

33
00:01:21,060 --> 00:01:22,800
This isn't always the case,

34
00:01:22,800 --> 00:01:24,810
as there have been a
few exceptions to this,

35
00:01:24,810 --> 00:01:26,970
like in the 2020 recession,

36
00:01:26,970 --> 00:01:31,680
as the S&P 500 returned
16.3% for that year.

37
00:01:31,680 --> 00:01:33,630
However, that isn't the norm.

38
00:01:33,630 --> 00:01:35,700
This makes sense as during a recession,

39
00:01:35,700 --> 00:01:39,000
less money is being spent
by people like you and me.

40
00:01:39,000 --> 00:01:41,190
Companies then start firing staff,

41
00:01:41,190 --> 00:01:43,440
leading to more people being unemployed,

42
00:01:43,440 --> 00:01:45,930
which causes people to spend even less.

43
00:01:45,930 --> 00:01:48,300
This results in companies
also earning less

44
00:01:48,300 --> 00:01:51,150
and, most of the time,
stock prices being impacted.

45
00:01:51,150 --> 00:01:54,060
This is one vicious cycle,
and I hope you can see

46
00:01:54,060 --> 00:01:57,300
why this would be a pretty
bad situation to be in.

47
00:01:57,300 --> 00:02:00,150
So if we aren't in a recession yet,

48
00:02:00,150 --> 00:02:02,490
why is the stock market going down?

49
00:02:02,490 --> 00:02:06,000
Well, as the stock market is
known as a leading indicator,

50
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:08,430
whenever there's a hint
of a recession happening,

51
00:02:08,430 --> 00:02:11,010
it reacts to that news pretty negatively.

52
00:02:11,010 --> 00:02:14,520
So you're probably thinking,
what was that hint?

53
00:02:14,520 --> 00:02:16,710
Well, several data reports showed

54
00:02:16,710 --> 00:02:20,790
that the US had only added
114,000 jobs in July,

55
00:02:20,790 --> 00:02:23,910
below expectations of about 150,000,

56
00:02:23,910 --> 00:02:27,480
and that unemployment had risen to 4.3%.

57
00:02:27,480 --> 00:02:31,140
This is higher than any
month since October 2021.

58
00:02:31,140 --> 00:02:34,020
Look, these numbers are
far from a disaster.

59
00:02:34,020 --> 00:02:36,750
The unemployment rate
is still relatively low,

60
00:02:36,750 --> 00:02:39,660
and the underperformance
in hiring isn't terrible.

61
00:02:39,660 --> 00:02:43,200
However, it has triggered
something known as the Sahm rule.

62
00:02:43,200 --> 00:02:46,380
This is a pretty cool
little rule that activates

63
00:02:46,380 --> 00:02:49,440
when the average unemployment
rate over three months

64
00:02:49,440 --> 00:02:52,140
goes up by at least 0.5%

65
00:02:52,140 --> 00:02:55,380
compared to its lowest
point over the past year.

66
00:02:55,380 --> 00:02:57,360
The reason people take this seriously

67
00:02:57,360 --> 00:02:59,190
is because it's accurately predicted

68
00:02:59,190 --> 00:03:01,950
every US recession since
the Second World War.

69
00:03:01,950 --> 00:03:04,770
In response, Goldman Sachs raised its odds

70
00:03:04,770 --> 00:03:09,300
of a recession occurring in
the next year from 15 to 25%.

71
00:03:09,300 --> 00:03:11,670
Interestingly, the woman
who came up with the rule,

72
00:03:11,670 --> 00:03:13,770
Claudia Sahm, doesn't think the law

73
00:03:13,770 --> 00:03:15,210
is gonna be right this time,

74
00:03:15,210 --> 00:03:16,650
and to put your mind at ease,

75
00:03:16,650 --> 00:03:18,870
there have been other
rules like this before,

76
00:03:18,870 --> 00:03:20,640
such as the bond yield curves

77
00:03:20,640 --> 00:03:23,190
that have turned out to
be unreliable recently.

78
00:03:23,190 --> 00:03:25,590
One reason why it might be a false alarm

79
00:03:25,590 --> 00:03:28,440
is that this time around,
unemployment isn't rising

80
00:03:28,440 --> 00:03:30,330
because people are losing their jobs.

81
00:03:30,330 --> 00:03:32,490
Instead, it's because more people

82
00:03:32,490 --> 00:03:33,990
are entering the workforce.

83
00:03:33,990 --> 00:03:35,820
However, as I mentioned before,

84
00:03:35,820 --> 00:03:38,130
unemployment rising is only one factor

85
00:03:38,130 --> 00:03:40,560
in a vicious cycle of a recession.

86
00:03:40,560 --> 00:03:41,790
The other important one

87
00:03:41,790 --> 00:03:44,580
is the amount of money
everyday people are spending.

88
00:03:44,580 --> 00:03:48,120
Unfortunately, it looks like
spending is slowing down, too.

89
00:03:48,120 --> 00:03:49,500
Now, it may sound odd,

90
00:03:49,500 --> 00:03:51,420
but a good way to gauge
this is by checking

91
00:03:51,420 --> 00:03:54,090
how companies like McDonald's
on Walmart are doing,

92
00:03:54,090 --> 00:03:56,220
and both have recently
said their customers

93
00:03:56,220 --> 00:03:57,810
are cutting back on spending.

94
00:03:57,810 --> 00:04:00,060
Another company to watch is Wayfair.

95
00:04:00,060 --> 00:04:02,130
I actually buy a lot of
my furniture from them.

96
00:04:02,130 --> 00:04:05,100
I'm actually sitting on a
Wayfair chair right now.

97
00:04:05,100 --> 00:04:06,240
They recently mentioned

98
00:04:06,240 --> 00:04:08,490
that customers are being very cautious,

99
00:04:08,490 --> 00:04:12,060
with spending down nearly
25% from three years ago.

100
00:04:12,060 --> 00:04:14,070
Now, this all sounds pretty worrying.

101
00:04:14,070 --> 00:04:16,470
However, when it comes to the Sahm rule,

102
00:04:16,470 --> 00:04:19,140
this time around, I'm taking
it with a pinch of salt.

103
00:04:19,140 --> 00:04:21,360
Even Goldman Sachs seem to agree.

104
00:04:21,360 --> 00:04:23,340
Although they've
increased their projection

105
00:04:23,340 --> 00:04:24,780
on the risk of recession,

106
00:04:24,780 --> 00:04:26,910
they still think it's pretty unlikely.

107
00:04:26,910 --> 00:04:28,170
There's also a lot of time

108
00:04:28,170 --> 00:04:30,150
for the big dogs at the Federal Reserve

109
00:04:30,150 --> 00:04:32,400
to swoop in and protect the economy,

110
00:04:32,400 --> 00:04:36,450
which leads me nicely onto
reason two is interest rates.

111
00:04:36,450 --> 00:04:38,460
Right, check out this graph.

112
00:04:38,460 --> 00:04:40,980
The last few times that
the Fed cut interest rates

113
00:04:40,980 --> 00:04:44,310
from their peak, a recession
followed closely behind.

114
00:04:44,310 --> 00:04:45,900
And guess what's just happened?

115
00:04:45,900 --> 00:04:48,930
You got it, the US Federal Reserve hinted,

116
00:04:48,930 --> 00:04:50,970
after its meeting at the end of July,

117
00:04:50,970 --> 00:04:53,160
that interest rates would soon be cut.

118
00:04:53,160 --> 00:04:55,500
Now, this graph also
looks pretty concerning.

119
00:04:55,500 --> 00:04:58,620
However, it really doesn't
show us the full picture.

120
00:04:58,620 --> 00:05:00,510
To understand why this time is different

121
00:05:00,510 --> 00:05:02,820
from those past examples on the graph,

122
00:05:02,820 --> 00:05:04,980
we need to look at why the Federal Reserve

123
00:05:04,980 --> 00:05:08,220
initially put interest rates up in 2022.

124
00:05:08,220 --> 00:05:11,460
The answer is simple. The pandemic hit.

125
00:05:11,460 --> 00:05:13,440
Money printers were on full blast,

126
00:05:13,440 --> 00:05:15,150
and supply chains were suffering,

127
00:05:15,150 --> 00:05:17,130
leading to high inflation levels.

128
00:05:17,130 --> 00:05:19,590
The only way to bring
prices back under control

129
00:05:19,590 --> 00:05:21,720
was to increase interest rates.

130
00:05:21,720 --> 00:05:24,030
This was an unprecedented situation,

131
00:05:24,030 --> 00:05:26,820
which I don't think we'll
see again in our lifetimes,

132
00:05:26,820 --> 00:05:27,990
certainly not in mine.

133
00:05:27,990 --> 00:05:31,200
When they did this, they set
an inflation rate target to hit

134
00:05:31,200 --> 00:05:32,820
and said they would start cutting rates

135
00:05:32,820 --> 00:05:34,320
once they achieved it.

136
00:05:34,320 --> 00:05:35,760
This strategy worked,

137
00:05:35,760 --> 00:05:38,700
and inflation has come
down pretty significantly

138
00:05:38,700 --> 00:05:42,480
from its peak of 9.1% in 2022.

139
00:05:42,480 --> 00:05:43,500
But it still remains

140
00:05:43,500 --> 00:05:46,470
slightly above the
Fed's target rate of 2%.

141
00:05:46,470 --> 00:05:48,960
So now if we go back to the graph,

142
00:05:48,960 --> 00:05:52,350
all those past examples of
the Fed cutting interest rates

143
00:05:52,350 --> 00:05:53,400
was because they were trying

144
00:05:53,400 --> 00:05:55,440
to stop a recession from happening.

145
00:05:55,440 --> 00:05:58,380
However, this time, it's
because are so close

146
00:05:58,380 --> 00:06:00,330
to hitting their inflation rate target.

147
00:06:00,330 --> 00:06:03,330
So the Fed cut in interest
rate should actually be seen

148
00:06:03,330 --> 00:06:05,460
as a positive move for investors,

149
00:06:05,460 --> 00:06:07,740
because it helps boost the economy.

150
00:06:07,740 --> 00:06:10,830
When rates are lower,
borrowing money becomes easier,

151
00:06:10,830 --> 00:06:12,900
which means more money flows around.

152
00:06:12,900 --> 00:06:15,570
This is the opposite of what
happens during a recession.

153
00:06:15,570 --> 00:06:18,510
So on the surface, lots of
these factors look worrying.

154
00:06:18,510 --> 00:06:20,400
However, when you dig a bit deeper,

155
00:06:20,400 --> 00:06:22,200
it doesn't seem as bad as it looks.

156
00:06:22,200 --> 00:06:25,740
So what else has caused the
markets to drop so much?

157
00:06:25,740 --> 00:06:28,920
That brings me on to
reason three, tech stocks.

158
00:06:28,920 --> 00:06:32,070
If you recently invested in
any of the top tech companies,

159
00:06:32,070 --> 00:06:34,590
then you were definitely
hit harder than most,

160
00:06:34,590 --> 00:06:38,310
especially the stocks in a group
known as the Magnificent 7,

161
00:06:38,310 --> 00:06:40,980
which include Apple, Amazon, Alphabet,

162
00:06:40,980 --> 00:06:43,950
Meta, Microsoft, Tesla, and NVIDIA.

163
00:06:43,950 --> 00:06:45,780
Now, you might be thinking, "That's fine.

164
00:06:45,780 --> 00:06:48,360
I don't invest in individual tech stocks."

165
00:06:48,360 --> 00:06:53,100
However, this also impacts the
S&P 500 Index Fund investors,

166
00:06:53,100 --> 00:06:56,070
as these top seven tech
stocks actually make up

167
00:06:56,070 --> 00:06:59,100
about 31% of the S&P 500,

168
00:06:59,100 --> 00:07:01,380
meaning that when tech
stocks get hit hard,

169
00:07:01,380 --> 00:07:03,150
so does the entire index fund.

170
00:07:03,150 --> 00:07:05,700
So I guess the obvious question is,

171
00:07:05,700 --> 00:07:07,590
why are tech stocks suffering?

172
00:07:07,590 --> 00:07:10,230
Well, recently these
stocks have been soaring

173
00:07:10,230 --> 00:07:14,100
due to the promise of
revolutionary AI technology.

174
00:07:14,100 --> 00:07:16,620
I went to a conference last year in Texas,

175
00:07:16,620 --> 00:07:18,990
and all they seemed to be banging on about

176
00:07:18,990 --> 00:07:21,030
was all these different AI tools

177
00:07:21,030 --> 00:07:22,950
I should be using in my business.

178
00:07:22,950 --> 00:07:25,290
I honestly got a bit
sick of hearing about it

179
00:07:25,290 --> 00:07:26,670
over and over again.

180
00:07:26,670 --> 00:07:28,620
It does seem like the AI craze

181
00:07:28,620 --> 00:07:30,480
has caused a bubble to form,

182
00:07:30,480 --> 00:07:32,400
pushing some stock prices higher

183
00:07:32,400 --> 00:07:33,630
than they should have ever been.

184
00:07:33,630 --> 00:07:36,780
Don't get me wrong. I do
definitely see the value in AI.

185
00:07:36,780 --> 00:07:38,640
It's not like the metaverse.

186
00:07:38,640 --> 00:07:40,380
Enough said about that, I think.

187
00:07:40,380 --> 00:07:43,680
I just think the value of
our current AI capabilities

188
00:07:43,680 --> 00:07:45,510
have been widely overvalued

189
00:07:45,510 --> 00:07:47,340
and that investors are realizing this,

190
00:07:47,340 --> 00:07:50,670
causing stock prices to fall
to more reasonable levels.

191
00:07:50,670 --> 00:07:52,230
I'm not alone with this thinking,

192
00:07:52,230 --> 00:07:55,230
as Warren Buffett's Berkshire
Hathaway slashed its stake

193
00:07:55,230 --> 00:07:58,620
in Apple by almost 50%
in the second quarter.

194
00:07:58,620 --> 00:08:00,300
There also seems to be bad news

195
00:08:00,300 --> 00:08:03,990
followed by more bad news
coming from the AI space.

196
00:08:03,990 --> 00:08:05,280
I mean, just recently,

197
00:08:05,280 --> 00:08:07,920
the first preview of
Apple Intelligence failed

198
00:08:07,920 --> 00:08:09,270
to live up to the hype,

199
00:08:09,270 --> 00:08:12,780
and NVIDIA's highly
anticipated Blackwell chips

200
00:08:12,780 --> 00:08:15,030
will be delayed due to design flaws.

201
00:08:15,030 --> 00:08:17,340
These chip delays will
also impact companies

202
00:08:17,340 --> 00:08:18,990
like Meta and Microsoft,

203
00:08:18,990 --> 00:08:21,900
so everything is pretty interconnected.

204
00:08:21,900 --> 00:08:23,280
Look, all in all,

205
00:08:23,280 --> 00:08:26,460
I personally think investors
got a little hyped about AI,

206
00:08:26,460 --> 00:08:28,320
and it became a bit of a buzzword.

207
00:08:28,320 --> 00:08:30,090
It reminds me of when I was investing

208
00:08:30,090 --> 00:08:33,210
during the dot-com
bubble in the late 1990s.

209
00:08:33,210 --> 00:08:36,510
Just keep in mind that the
stocks with the sharpest booms

210
00:08:36,510 --> 00:08:37,980
tend to fall the furthest.

211
00:08:37,980 --> 00:08:41,130
Reason four is the Japanese yen.

212
00:08:41,130 --> 00:08:44,640
Now, imagine you discover
this really clever loophole.

213
00:08:44,640 --> 00:08:48,000
You borrow money from someone
with virtually no interest

214
00:08:48,000 --> 00:08:49,830
and invest it wisely.

215
00:08:49,830 --> 00:08:53,670
Meanwhile, the currency's
value drops significantly.

216
00:08:53,670 --> 00:08:55,800
By the time you need to repay the loan,

217
00:08:55,800 --> 00:08:57,720
the money you owe is worth much less

218
00:08:57,720 --> 00:08:58,950
than when you borrowed it,

219
00:08:58,950 --> 00:09:00,780
but your investment has grown,

220
00:09:00,780 --> 00:09:03,990
so you end up repaying
the devalued currency

221
00:09:03,990 --> 00:09:06,330
while profiting from
your investment's growth.

222
00:09:06,330 --> 00:09:09,180
Now, that would be a pretty
cool life hack, right?

223
00:09:09,180 --> 00:09:11,880
Well, it's exactly what
lots of traders were doing

224
00:09:11,880 --> 00:09:13,200
with the Japanese yen,

225
00:09:13,200 --> 00:09:15,840
as it's been falling
in value for years now.

226
00:09:15,840 --> 00:09:17,760
It's a little more complicated than that,

227
00:09:17,760 --> 00:09:20,130
but I'm not gonna bore
you with all the details.

228
00:09:20,130 --> 00:09:22,560
It's a cool trick to make some easy money.

229
00:09:22,560 --> 00:09:24,300
But why am I telling you this?

230
00:09:24,300 --> 00:09:27,240
Well, everything changed when
the Bank of Japan decided

231
00:09:27,240 --> 00:09:30,030
to raise its main interest
rate from nearly zero,

232
00:09:30,030 --> 00:09:33,660
so once again, countries
messing with the interest rates.

233
00:09:33,660 --> 00:09:35,340
This small change caused the value

234
00:09:35,340 --> 00:09:37,170
of the Japanese yen to increase,

235
00:09:37,170 --> 00:09:40,020
meaning that everyone using
the loophole I just described

236
00:09:40,020 --> 00:09:41,760
were a little bit screwed,

237
00:09:41,760 --> 00:09:44,280
as they had to sell their
assets to cover their losses.

238
00:09:44,280 --> 00:09:46,800
Some experts believed that
this could be contributing

239
00:09:46,800 --> 00:09:49,050
to the current decline
in the stock market.

240
00:09:49,050 --> 00:09:50,340
Since all this went down,

241
00:09:50,340 --> 00:09:52,560
the Bank of Japan has
eased up on the torque

242
00:09:52,560 --> 00:09:54,660
of raising interest rates again.

243
00:09:54,660 --> 00:09:56,550
This has made the yen drop a bit,

244
00:09:56,550 --> 00:09:57,510
which has gone some way

245
00:09:57,510 --> 00:09:59,880
to help calm the worries
that a stronger yen

246
00:09:59,880 --> 00:10:02,520
could mess with the global
stock market once again.

247
00:10:02,520 --> 00:10:04,770
So as you can see, there
are lots of reasons

248
00:10:04,770 --> 00:10:07,020
behind the recent stock market decline.

249
00:10:07,020 --> 00:10:08,580
Now that you have all the facts,

250
00:10:08,580 --> 00:10:10,710
let me give you my
thoughts on all of this,

251
00:10:10,710 --> 00:10:13,440
and how you can adjust
your investing strategy.

252
00:10:13,440 --> 00:10:15,930
As always, I'm not a financial advisor,

253
00:10:15,930 --> 00:10:18,600
and none of this should be
taken as financial advice.

254
00:10:18,600 --> 00:10:20,640
I'm just speaking from years of experience

255
00:10:20,640 --> 00:10:23,790
actually investing and seeing
situations like this happen

256
00:10:23,790 --> 00:10:25,380
time and time again.

257
00:10:25,380 --> 00:10:27,510
Firstly, throughout my investing journey,

258
00:10:27,510 --> 00:10:29,910
one phrase has always served me well:

259
00:10:29,910 --> 00:10:31,830
buy when there's blood in the water.

260
00:10:31,830 --> 00:10:34,710
In other words, when the
stock market is in decline,

261
00:10:34,710 --> 00:10:36,450
and people are panic-selling,

262
00:10:36,450 --> 00:10:39,060
pushing prices down to irrational levels,

263
00:10:39,060 --> 00:10:41,430
that's the time to step in and invest.

264
00:10:41,430 --> 00:10:43,687
Another phrase that
teaches the same thing is,

265
00:10:43,687 --> 00:10:44,670
"Buy the dip."

266
00:10:44,670 --> 00:10:46,260
I know it should go without saying,

267
00:10:46,260 --> 00:10:47,490
but if you want to do this,

268
00:10:47,490 --> 00:10:49,830
then you need to make sure
you have an emergency fund

269
00:10:49,830 --> 00:10:52,950
of at least three to five
months of your living expenses.

270
00:10:52,950 --> 00:10:54,450
This is more crucial than ever,

271
00:10:54,450 --> 00:10:56,850
as the stock market is
in a turbulent time,

272
00:10:56,850 --> 00:10:58,050
and you don't wanna be forced

273
00:10:58,050 --> 00:10:59,670
to sell your stocks at a loss

274
00:10:59,670 --> 00:11:02,400
only to find out later
that if you'd held them,

275
00:11:02,400 --> 00:11:04,500
then you'd actually have come out ahead.

276
00:11:04,500 --> 00:11:07,140
Look, nobody can predict
if the stock market

277
00:11:07,140 --> 00:11:09,480
is gonna go up or continue downwards.

278
00:11:09,480 --> 00:11:12,510
However, I've always come
out on top eventually

279
00:11:12,510 --> 00:11:13,890
by dollar-cost-averaging

280
00:11:13,890 --> 00:11:18,270
into a low-cost S&P 500
Index Fund as it declines.

281
00:11:18,270 --> 00:11:20,940
This essentially just means
buying at regular intervals

282
00:11:20,940 --> 00:11:22,260
as the price drops.

283
00:11:22,260 --> 00:11:24,510
This could be every day or every week.

284
00:11:24,510 --> 00:11:26,670
For all the people that have
been watching my videos,

285
00:11:26,670 --> 00:11:28,410
waiting for the perfect chance

286
00:11:28,410 --> 00:11:30,090
to jump in and start investing,

287
00:11:30,090 --> 00:11:33,060
if I was in your shoes,
I'd start my journey now.

288
00:11:33,060 --> 00:11:35,010
Yes, you can't guarantee returns,

289
00:11:35,010 --> 00:11:37,350
but at least you're entering
at a lower price point.

