303
00:12:04,530 --> 00:12:07,320
Secondly, make sure you're diversified.

304
00:12:07,320 --> 00:12:09,180
This basically means spreading your money

305
00:12:09,180 --> 00:12:11,040
across different baskets of assets

306
00:12:11,040 --> 00:12:13,890
like stocks, bonds, and even crypto.

307
00:12:13,890 --> 00:12:16,260
This is key to reducing investment risk

308
00:12:16,260 --> 00:12:19,230
and smoothing the ride
through a crazy market.

309
00:12:19,230 --> 00:12:21,960
So if one stock or industry has a bad day,

310
00:12:21,960 --> 00:12:24,630
your other investments may
help offset those losses.

311
00:12:24,630 --> 00:12:27,150
If you're an index fund investor like me,

312
00:12:27,150 --> 00:12:29,460
then you'll be pretty diversified anyway.

313
00:12:29,460 --> 00:12:31,800
But bear in mind that the S&P 500

314
00:12:31,800 --> 00:12:34,080
is top-heavy with tech companies,

315
00:12:34,080 --> 00:12:35,550
so it might be worth investing

316
00:12:35,550 --> 00:12:38,010
in a Total US Stock Market Fund

317
00:12:38,010 --> 00:12:40,320
to get even more diversification.

318
00:12:40,320 --> 00:12:42,990
Thirdly, keep your eye on the long game.

319
00:12:42,990 --> 00:12:45,990
It's easy to be positive when
your portfolio is growing,

320
00:12:45,990 --> 00:12:47,820
but when things start to go a bit south,

321
00:12:47,820 --> 00:12:49,620
and your gains start disappearing,

322
00:12:49,620 --> 00:12:52,290
it can be really tempting
to sell everything.

323
00:12:52,290 --> 00:12:53,250
I've been there,

324
00:12:53,250 --> 00:12:55,920
but holding on has
always worked out for me.

325
00:12:55,920 --> 00:12:58,530
Trying to guess the best
times to buy and sell stocks

326
00:12:58,530 --> 00:13:01,500
is really tough and often
leads to missed chances,

327
00:13:01,500 --> 00:13:02,940
according to Charles Schwab.

328
00:13:02,940 --> 00:13:05,310
Remember, if you sell
when the market is down,

329
00:13:05,310 --> 00:13:07,410
you're making those losses permanent.

330
00:13:07,410 --> 00:13:11,640
For example, during the COVID
market crash in February 2020,

331
00:13:11,640 --> 00:13:15,840
if you had $1,000 in an
ETF, tracking the S&P 500,

332
00:13:15,840 --> 00:13:18,660
it would've lost over 30% of its value.

333
00:13:18,660 --> 00:13:21,630
Selling then would've
locked in those losses.

334
00:13:21,630 --> 00:13:22,860
But if you'd held on,

335
00:13:22,860 --> 00:13:25,740
you would've seen your
investment bounce back by August,

336
00:13:25,740 --> 00:13:26,730
just seven months.

337
00:13:26,730 --> 00:13:28,770
If you're waiting to
jump back into the market

338
00:13:28,770 --> 00:13:30,000
when things look better,

339
00:13:30,000 --> 00:13:31,710
you'll probably end up paying more

340
00:13:31,710 --> 00:13:33,930
and missing out on the rebound gains.

341
00:13:33,930 --> 00:13:35,700
So all in all, remember,

342
00:13:35,700 --> 00:13:38,460
the US economy still remains pretty strong

343
00:13:38,460 --> 00:13:40,230
